{"title_page": "Walter Gorini", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian cyclist}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n|name=\n|image=Luigi Borghetti and Walter Gorini 1968cr.jpg\n| image_size     = 280px\n|caption=Luigi Borghetti and Walter Gorini (right) at the 1968 Olympics\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|df=y|1944|8|29}}\n|birth_place=[[Cotignola]], Italy\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n| height = {{convert|1.72|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|71|kg|lb|abbr=on}}\n|sport=Cycling\n|club=\n|alma_mater=\n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalCountry|{{ITA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UCI Track Cycling World Championships|Track World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|1966 Frankfurt|Tandem}}\n{{MedalGold|1968 Rome|Tandem}}\n}}\n'''Walter Gorini''' (born 29 August 1944) is a retired Italian track cyclist who was active between 1966 and 1967. He won one bronze and one gold medals in the tandem at the world championships of 1966 and 1968, respectively (both with [[Giordano Turrini]]); he finished fourth in this event at the [[1968 Summer Olympics]] (with [[Luigi Borghetti]]).<ref name=r1/><ref name=r2/>\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=r1>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/go/walter-gorini-1.html Walter Gorini]. sports-reference.com</ref>\n<ref name=r2>[http://www.cyclingarchives.com/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=27702 Walter Gorini]. cyclingarchives.com</ref>\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gorini, Walter}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Italy]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1968 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Ravenna]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Emilia-Romagna]]\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1940s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox sportsperson\n|name=\n|image=Luigi Borghetti and Walter Gorini 1968cr.jpg\n| image_size     = 280px\n|caption=Luigi Borghetti and Walter Gorini (right) at the 1968 Olympics\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|df=y|1944|8|29}}\n|birth_place=[[Cotignola]], Italy\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n| height = {{convert|1.72|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|71|kg|lb|abbr=on}}\n|sport=Cycling\n|club=\n|alma_mater=\n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalCountry|{{ITA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UCI Track Cycling World Championships|Track World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|1966 Frankfurt|Tandem}}\n{{MedalGold|1968 Rome|Tandem}}\n}}\n'''Walter Gorini''' (born 29 August 1944) is a retired Italian track cyclist who was active between 1966 and 1967. He won one bronze and one gold medals in the tandem at the world championships of 1966 and 1968, respectively (both with [[Giordano Turrini]]); he finished fourth in this event at the [[1968 Summer Olympics]] (with [[Luigi Borghetti]]).<ref name=r1/><ref name=r2/>\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=r1>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/go/walter-gorini-1.html Walter Gorini]. sports-reference.com</ref>\n<ref name=r2>[http://www.cyclingarchives.com/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=27702 Walter Gorini]. cyclingarchives.com</ref>\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gorini, Walter}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Italy]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1968 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Ravenna]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Emilia-Romagna]]\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1940s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walter_Gorini"}
{"title_page": "Allan Carr", "text_new": "{{about|the American stage and film producer|the British comedian|Alan Carr|other people with a similar name|Alan Carr (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                  = Allan Carr\n| image                 = Allan Carr at 1989 Academy Awards.jpg\n| caption               = Allan Carr at the 1989 Academy Awards\n| birth_name            = Allan Solomon\n| birth_date            = {{Birth date|1937|05|27}}\n| birth_place           = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_date            = {{Death date and age|1999|06|29|1937|05|27}}\n| death_place           = [[Beverly Hills, California]], U.S.\n| nationality           = American\n| education             = [[Lake Forest College]]\n| alma_mater            = [[Northwestern University]]\n| occupation            = Producer, screenwriter\n| years_active          = 1969\u20131998\n}}\n\n'''Allan Carr''' (born '''Allan Soloman''', May 27, 1937 \u2013 June 29, 1999) was an American producer and manager of stage for the [[film|screen]]. Carr was nominated for numerous awards, winning a [[Tony Award]] and two [[People's Choice Awards]], and was named Producer of the Year by the National Association of Theatre Owners.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news| url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_1999_June_30/ai_55029330|work=Business Wire|title=Allan Carr, Producer, Impresario, Manager and Showman, Dies at 62|date=June 30, 1999}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nCarr was born '''Allan Solomon'''<ref>[http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20074272,00.html People Magazine: \"Producer Allan Carr Waxes Fat and Fortyish on the Gross of Grease\" By Sue Reilly] August 06, 1979</ref> to an [[American Jewish]] family<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iqRezpQzUcAC&q=jewish#v=onepage&q=jewish%2C%20or%20not&f=false|first=Robert|last=Hofler|title=Party Animals: A Hollywood Tale of Sex, Drugs, and Rock N Roll Starring the Fabulous Allan Carr|pages=95|publisher=|date=Dec 28, 2012|isbn=9781459600072}}</ref> in Chicago, Illinois. He attended [[Lake Forest College]] and [[Northwestern University]], but his interest was always in show business. While at Northwestern, he invested $750 in the Broadway musical ''Ziegfeld Follies,'' starring [[Tallulah Bankhead]]. Though the show was not a hit, he had also invested $1,250 in 1967's ''[[The Happiest Millionaire]],'' which gave him the success he needed to leave school and embark upon a career in entertainment.\n\nIn Chicago in the 1960s, he opened the Civic Theater and financed ''[[The World of Carl Sandburg]]'' starring [[Bette Davis]] and [[Gary Merrill]], as well as [[Eva Le Gallienne]] in ''[[Mary Stuart (play)|Mary Stuart]],'' directed by Sir [[Tyrone Guthrie]], and [[Tennessee Williams]]'s ''Garden District'', featuring [[Cathleen Nesbitt]] and [[Diana Barrymore]]. Carr worked behind the scenes at ''[[Playboy]]'' with [[Hugh Hefner]] and was a co-creator of the ''Playboy Penthouse'' television series, which in turn launched the [[Playboy Club]]s.\n\nThrough the years, he became known as a great planner of promotional events and parties. One such event, a black-tie affair for [[Truman Capote]], took place in an abandoned Los Angeles jail.<ref name=Y>{{cite web|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/allan-carr-rise-fall-hollywood-hedonist-014130665.html|title=Allan Carr: The rise and fall of a Hollywood hedonist|author=Taggart, Frankie|date=May 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Management career==\nIn 1966, Carr founded the talent agency Allan Carr Enterprises, managing the actors [[Tony Curtis]], [[Peter Sellers]],<ref name=Y/> [[Rosalind Russell]], [[Dyan Cannon]], [[Melina Mercouri]], and [[Marlo Thomas]].  Some of the other entertainment figures whose careers he managed were [[Ann-Margret]], a string of whose television specials he also produced, [[Nancy Walker]], [[Marvin Hamlisch]], [[Joan Rivers]], [[Peggy Lee]], \"Mama\" [[Cass Elliot]],<ref name=Y/> [[Paul Anka]], [[Frankie Valli and the Four Seasons]], [[George Maharis]], and [[Herb Alpert and the Tijuana Brass]].\n\nCarr is also credited for having discovered numerous celebrities, including some such, who also became his clients, as [[Olivia Newton-John]], [[Mark Hamill]], [[Michelle Pfeiffer]],<ref>[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/96824/Allan-Carr Allan Carr \u2013 Britannica Online Encyclopedia<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> [[Steve Guttenberg]],<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/07/01/arts/allan-carr-62-the-producer-of-grease-and-la-cage.html|work=The New York Times|title=Allan Carr, 62, the Producer Of 'Grease' and 'La Cage'|date=July 1, 1999|accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref> and [[Lisa Hartman]].<ref name=autogenerated1/>\n\n==''Grease'' and Broadway success==\nProducer [[Robert Stigwood]] hired him in 1975 as marketing and promotion consultant, with his first project being for the [[Tommy (1975 film)|film version]] of the [[rock opera]] ''[[The Who's Tommy|Tommy]]''.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> The film was a hit and he expanded his involvement for his next film, re-editing and overdubbing a low-budget foreign film about a real-life disaster. The result was ''Survive!'' (The disaster in question was also described in Piers Paul Read's book ''Alive.'') The surprise box office success of ''Survive!'' in 1976 made Carr a wealthy man and gave him clout at [[Paramount Pictures]].\n\nIn 1977, Stigwood asked him to produce the ad campaign for ''[[Saturday Night Fever]],'' and he turned the film's premiere into a star-studded television special. It worked so well that Stigwood gave him ''[[Grease (film)|Grease]]'' (1978). Carr not only helmed the ad campaign and produced the premiere party and television special for ''Grease,'' but also wrote the screenplay and co-produced the film for six million dollars, casting his then client [[Olivia Newton-John]].<ref name=Y/> It became the highest-grossing film of the year, and one of the highest-grossing films up until that time, at just under $100 million. The film was nominated for five [[Golden Globe Awards]] and won two [[People's Choice Awards]], for Best Picture and Best Musical Picture. That year he even appeared in a role on the final season of the [[Angie Dickinson]] television series ''[[Police Woman (TV series)|Police Woman]]''. Stigwood and Carr would work on several other films, including 1978 [[Academy Award|Oscar]]-winner ''[[The Deer Hunter]]''.\n\nThe following year, 1979, he produced the [[Village People]] film musical ''[[Can't Stop the Music|Can't Stop The Music]],''<ref name=Y/> a production which, while campy, steered clear of addressing the band members' presumed homosexuality in the script. Again he orchestrated a lavish series of premieres and a television special that co-starred his friends Hefner and [[Cher]]. But the film was released in 1980, after the crash of the disco craze, and as a result, it was a major flop.<ref name=Y/> Because of this, Carr \"won\" the first annual [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Picture]] in 1981. Undaunted, he went on to produce ''[[Grease 2]]'' (1982) which, while nowhere near the hit of its predecessor, was not the financial loss that ''Can't Stop The Music'' had been.\n\nWhen Carr was in Paris for the premiere of ''Grease,'' a friend took him to see a play about a gay couple, ''[[La Cage aux Folles (play)|La Cage aux Folles]].'' By this time in his career, Carr was ready to face the gay theme head on. Returning to Broadway he produced a musical version of the 1973 play,<ref name=Y/> which had since been made into a French film, and would later be remade as an American film called ''[[The Birdcage]].'' With a book by [[Harvey Fierstein]] and music and lyrics by [[Jerry Herman]], the show opened in 1983 and was a huge success, running for five years and 1,761 performances.  Nominated in 1984 for eight [[Drama Desk Award]]s and eight [[Tony Award]]s, the show won three Drama Desks and an impressive six Tonys, including a \"Best Musical\" win for Carr.\n\n==Snow White and the Academy Awards==\nCarr's reputation for hosting expensive and lavish parties and creating spectacular production numbers led [[AMPAS]]  to hire him to produce the [[61st Academy Awards]] and create the show based on his promise that he would turn it around from the dry, dull show it had been in previous years. It was inspired by ''[[Beach Blanket Babylon]]'', the musical revue show featuring [[Snow White]] at Hollywood after the dwarves during the [[Golden Age of Hollywood]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_AyU_EbgFlc Bruce Vilanch on \"The 1989 Oscars\" with Rob Lowe and Snow White - FoundationINTERVIEWS on YouTube]</ref> Promising \"the antithesis of tacky,\" and despite the best Nielson ratings in five years, it proved to be a career disaster for Allan, culminating in the infamous pairing of Snow White (played by Eileen Bowman) and [[Rob Lowe]] singing a parody of \"[[Proud Mary]].\"<ref name=Y/> Before that, when Snow White first entered the theater from the rear, she seemed to surprise and even put-off the movie stars she was singing to, using a high-pitched imitation (bordering on parody) of the Disney cartoon. During the main number, before Rob Lowe's entrance, a crooning Merv Griffin introduced a procession of once famous Hollywood stars ranging from Alice Faye to Roy Rogers and Dale Evans to Vincent Price, which seemed more forced than natural as the elders were practically guided across the stage by male dancers (some dressed as chairs and tables). Also, there was no host that year. Instead, actors and actresses traded off, ranging from Tom Selleck (who opened) to Bob Hope and Lucille Ball (the latter died three weeks later). His no host theme was centered on \"compadres, costars, couples and companions,\" and his no host theme wouldn't be repeated until the Oscars of 2019.\n\nThe telecast also included a production number featuring what was introduced as \"The Stars of Tomorrow\" doing a number entitled \"I Wanna Be An Oscar Winner\" with all the participants being actors and actresses ranging from the age group of late teens to mid-20s (including Corey Feldman doing a Michael Jackson impression; Christian Slater sword fighting with Tyrone Power Jr.; Chad Lowe shouting \"I am a Thespian\"; Tracy Nelson ballet dancing; Patrick Dempsey tap dancing along the central set stairwell).<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uAQ9Taunh7w The Stars of Tomorrow: 1989 Oscars]</ref> Due largely to the show's opening number, and despite the shows stellar Nielson ratings, the show became a laughing-stock and went down in history as one of the worst moments in awards show and television history.  [[The Walt Disney Company]] sued for allegedly illegal use of Snow White's image.<ref>[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/looking-back-oscars-biggest-goof-21211 Looking back at Oscar's biggest goof|Hollywood Reporter]</ref> Meanwhile, Gregory Peck (a personal friend of Carr's) and a number of actors wrote and signed a letter of protest, demanding there never be a show like that again; Peck, in fact, threatened to return his past Oscar if it was ever repeated, which it wasn't. \n\nCarr's reputation in Hollywood never fully recovered from this setback, although his decision to change the award announcement from \"And the winner is...\" to \"And the Oscar goes to...\"<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PT7g5pWzOyw Why the 1989 Oscars Are the Worst Ever - Metaflix on YouTube]</ref> became the norm for awards shows in general, not just for the Oscars. Carr also first hired comedian [[Bruce Vilanch]] as head comedy writer of the show, a job Vilanch still held as of 2015 (Vilanch was redeemed the following year since his old friend Billy Crystal hosted for his first of many times: with Vilanch as his head writer).\n\n==Later work==\nThat same year Carr helmed the project ''Goya...A Life in Song'' with Freddie Gershon and CBS Records, a concept album and, later, an off-Broadway musical theater production written by [[Maury Yeston]] (''[[Nine (musical)|Nine]]'') and featuring [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]] as artist [[Francisco Goya]].  Still in development for a full Broadway production, the music has been recorded by Domingo with [[Dionne Warwick]] in English and [[Gloria Estefan]] in Spanish, and a version of the duet \"[[Till I Loved You (song)|Till I Loved You]]\" was a top 40 single for [[Barbra Streisand]] and [[Don Johnson]].\n\nCarr continued his work in theater, sponsoring the 1995 [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] productions of ''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (play)|Cyrano de Bergerac]]'' and ''[[Much Ado About Nothing]]'' at [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]]'s [[Kennedy Center]] and Broadway's [[Gershwin Theatre]]<ref>[https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1999-jun-30-mn-51594-story.html Allan Carr; Producer of 'Grease' and 'La Cage aux Folles' - Los Angeles Times]</ref>, earning 10 Tony nominations between them including one more for Carr.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/obituary-allan-carr-1105920.html Obituary: Allan Carr|The Independent]</ref>\nCarr had returned to [[Paramount Pictures]] to handle the re-release of ''[[Grease (film)|Grease]]'' in 1998, which included producing a [[VH1]] television special of the twentieth anniversary Hollywood \"premiere\" screening and party, and special edition re-releases of the video, DVD, and soundtrack album.\n\n==Production career==\nCarr was a film producer for numerous movies, including:\n*''[[The First Time (1969 film)|The First Time]]'' (1969)\n*''[[C.C. and Company]]'' (1970)\n*''[[Grease (film)|Grease]]'' (1978)\n*''[[Can't Stop the Music]]'' (1980)\n*''[[Grease 2]]'' (1982)\n*''[[Where the Boys Are '84]]'' (1984)\n*''[[Cloak & Dagger (1984 film)|Cloak & Dagger]]'' (1984)\n\n==Personal life and death==\nCarr died on June 29, 1999, in [[Beverly Hills, California]] from [[liver cancer]].<ref name=Y/> At the time of his death, he split his time between his homes in Beverly Hills and [[Palm Springs, California|Palm Springs]], and was working on bringing [[Ken Ludwig]]'s Tony-winning comedy ''[[Lend Me a Tenor]]'' to Australia and the UK, and was preparing a new Broadway show, ''The New Musical Adventures of Tom Sawyer''.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\nHis ashes were scattered at sea by Ann-Margret, Roger Smith and Martin Menard in front of his former Diamond Head estate on the island of Oahu, Hawaii.\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 2017 a documentary about Carr's life was released entitled ''[[The Fabulous Allan Carr]]''.  The director of ''The Fabulous Allan Carr'' [[Jeffrey Schwarz]] said, \"Although it was no secret that Allan Carr was gay, he never formally acknowledged it publicly. The word 'flamboyant' was used to describe him, a code word.\"<ref name=Y/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0139591}}\n* {{Find a Grave|23458|accessdate=September 14, 2010}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9mronRVvdmw The infamous 1989 opening of the Oscars on YouTube]\n* [https://vimeo.com/221448144 The same opening also on Vimeo]\n\n{{Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Screenplay 1980\u20132000}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carr, Allan}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[[Category:Film producers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Television producers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Jewish American screenwriters]]\n[[Category:LGBT Jews]]\n[[Category:Gay entertainers]]\n[[Category:LGBT businesspeople from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from California]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Illinois]]\n[[Category:American theatre managers and producers]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in California]]\n[[Category:Deaths from liver cancer]]\n[[Category:Lake Forest College alumni]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Writers from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Tony Award winners]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Television producers from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Illinois]]\n[[Category:LGBT producers]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the American stage and film producer|the British comedian|Alan Carr|other people with a similar name|Alan Carr (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                  = Allan Carr\n| image                 = Allan Carr at 1989 Academy Awards.jpg\n| caption               = Allan Carr at the 1989 Academy Awards\n| birth_name            = Allan Solomon\n| birth_date            = {{Birth date|1937|05|27}}\n| birth_place           = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_date            = {{Death date and age|1999|06|29|1937|05|27}}\n| death_place           = [[Beverly Hills, California]], U.S.\n| nationality           = American\n| education             = [[Lake Forest College]]\n| alma_mater            = [[Northwestern University]]\n| occupation            = Producer, screenwriter\n| years_active          = 1969\u20131998\n}}\n\n'''Allan Carr''' (born '''Allan Soloman''', May 27, 1937 \u2013 June 29, 1999) was an American producer and manager of stage for the [[film|screen]]. Carr was nominated for numerous awards, winning a [[Tony Award]] and two [[People's Choice Awards]], and was named Producer of the Year by the National Association of Theatre Owners.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news| url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_1999_June_30/ai_55029330|work=Business Wire|title=Allan Carr, Producer, Impresario, Manager and Showman, Dies at 62|date=June 30, 1999}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nCarr was born '''Allan Solomon'''<ref>[http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20074272,00.html People Magazine: \"Producer Allan Carr Waxes Fat and Fortyish on the Gross of Grease\" By Sue Reilly] August 06, 1979</ref> to an [[American Jewish]] family<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iqRezpQzUcAC&q=jewish#v=onepage&q=jewish%2C%20or%20not&f=false|first=Robert|last=Hofler|title=Party Animals: A Hollywood Tale of Sex, Drugs, and Rock N Roll Starring the Fabulous Allan Carr|pages=95|publisher=|date=Dec 28, 2012|isbn=9781459600072}}</ref> in Chicago, Illinois. He attended [[Lake Forest College]] and [[Northwestern University]], but his interest was always in show business. While at Northwestern, he invested $750 in the Broadway musical ''Ziegfeld Follies,'' starring [[Tallulah Bankhead]]. Though the show was not a hit, he had also invested $1,250 in 1967's ''[[The Happiest Millionaire]],'' which gave him the success he needed to leave school and embark upon a career in entertainment.\n\nIn Chicago in the 1960s, he opened the Civic Theater and financed ''[[The World of Carl Sandburg]]'' starring [[Bette Davis]] and [[Gary Merrill]], as well as [[Eva Le Gallienne]] in ''[[Mary Stuart (play)|Mary Stuart]],'' directed by Sir [[Tyrone Guthrie]], and [[Tennessee Williams]]'s ''Garden District'', featuring [[Cathleen Nesbitt]] and [[Diana Barrymore]]. Carr worked behind the scenes at ''[[Playboy]]'' with [[Hugh Hefner]] and was a co-creator of the ''Playboy Penthouse'' television series, which in turn launched the [[Playboy Club]]s.\n\nThrough the years, he became known as a great planner of promotional events and parties. One such event, a black-tie affair for [[Truman Capote]], took place in an abandoned Los Angeles jail.<ref name=Y>{{cite web|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/allan-carr-rise-fall-hollywood-hedonist-014130665.html|title=Allan Carr: The rise and fall of a Hollywood hedonist|author=Taggart, Frankie|date=May 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Management career==\nIn 1966, Carr founded the talent agency Allan Carr Enterprises, managing the actors [[Tony Curtis]], [[Peter Sellers]],<ref name=Y/> [[Rosalind Russell]], [[Dyan Cannon]], [[Melina Mercouri]], and [[Marlo Thomas]].  Some of the other entertainment figures whose careers he managed were [[Ann-Margret]], a string of whose television specials he also produced, [[Nancy Walker]], [[Marvin Hamlisch]], [[Joan Rivers]], [[Peggy Lee]], \"Mama\" [[Cass Elliot]],<ref name=Y/> [[Paul Anka]], [[Frankie Valli and the Four Seasons]], [[George Maharis]], and [[Herb Alpert and the Tijuana Brass]].\n\nCarr is also credited for having discovered numerous celebrities, including some such, who also became his clients, as [[Olivia Newton-John]], [[Mark Hamill]], [[Michelle Pfeiffer]],<ref>[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/96824/Allan-Carr Allan Carr \u2013 Britannica Online Encyclopedia<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> [[Steve Guttenberg]],<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/07/01/arts/allan-carr-62-the-producer-of-grease-and-la-cage.html|work=The New York Times|title=Allan Carr, 62, the Producer Of 'Grease' and 'La Cage'|date=July 1, 1999|accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref> and [[Lisa Hartman]].<ref name=autogenerated1/>\n\n==''Grease'' and Broadway success==\nProducer [[Robert Stigwood]] hired him in 1975 as marketing and promotion consultant, with his first project being for the [[Tommy (1975 film)|film version]] of the [[rock opera]] ''[[The Who's Tommy|Tommy]]''.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> The film was a hit and he expanded his involvement for his next film, re-editing and overdubbing a low-budget foreign film about a real-life disaster. The result was ''Survive!'' (The disaster in question was also described in Piers Paul Read's book ''Alive.'') The surprise box office success of ''Survive!'' in 1976 made Carr a wealthy man and gave him clout at [[Paramount Pictures]].\n\nIn 1977, Stigwood asked him to produce the ad campaign for ''[[Saturday Night Fever]],'' and he turned the film's premiere into a star-studded television special. It worked so well that Stigwood gave him ''[[Grease (film)|Grease]]'' (1978). Carr not only helmed the ad campaign and produced the premiere party and television special for ''Grease,'' but also wrote the screenplay and co-produced the film for six million dollars, casting his then client [[Olivia Newton-John]].<ref name=Y/> It became the highest-grossing film of the year, and one of the highest-grossing films up until that time, at just under $100 million. The film was nominated for five [[Golden Globe Awards]] and won two [[People's Choice Awards]], for Best Picture and Best Musical Picture. That year he even appeared in a role on the final season of the [[Angie Dickinson]] television series ''[[Police Woman (TV series)|Police Woman]]''. Stigwood and Carr would work on several other films, including 1978 [[Academy Award|Oscar]]-winner ''[[The Deer Hunter]]''.\n\nThe following year, 1979, he produced the [[Village People]] film musical ''[[Can't Stop the Music|Can't Stop The Music]],''<ref name=Y/> a production which, while campy, steered clear of addressing the band members' presumed homosexuality in the script. Again he orchestrated a lavish series of premieres and a television special that co-starred his friends Hefner and [[Cher]]. But the film was released in 1980, after the crash of the disco craze, and as a result, it was a major flop.<ref name=Y/> Because of this, Carr \"won\" the first annual [[Golden Raspberry Award]] for Worst Film, in 1981. Undaunted, he went on to produce ''[[Grease 2]]'' (1982) which, while nowhere near the hit of its predecessor, was not the financial loss that ''Can't Stop The Music'' had been.\n\nWhen Carr was in Paris for the premiere of ''Grease,'' a friend took him to see a play about a gay couple, ''[[La Cage aux Folles (play)|La Cage aux Folles]].'' By this time in his career, Carr was ready to face the gay theme head on. Returning to Broadway he produced a musical version of the 1973 play,<ref name=Y/> which had since been made into a French film, and would later be remade as an American film called ''[[The Birdcage]].'' With a book by [[Harvey Fierstein]] and music and lyrics by [[Jerry Herman]], the show opened in 1983 and was a huge success, running for five years and 1,761 performances.  Nominated in 1984 for eight [[Drama Desk Award]]s and eight [[Tony Award]]s, the show won three Drama Desks and an impressive six Tonys, including a \"Best Musical\" win for Carr.\n\n==Snow White and the Academy Awards==\nCarr's reputation for hosting expensive and lavish parties and creating spectacular production numbers led [[AMPAS]]  to hire him to produce the [[61st Academy Awards]] and create the show based on his promise that he would turn it around from the dry, dull show it had been in previous years. It was inspired by ''[[Beach Blanket Babylon]]'', the musical revue show featuring [[Snow White]] at Hollywood after the dwarves during the [[Golden Age of Hollywood]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_AyU_EbgFlc Bruce Vilanch on \"The 1989 Oscars\" with Rob Lowe and Snow White - FoundationINTERVIEWS on YouTube]</ref> Promising \"the antithesis of tacky,\" and despite the best Nielson ratings in five years, it proved to be a career disaster for Allan, culminating in the infamous pairing of Snow White (played by Eileen Bowman) and [[Rob Lowe]] singing a parody of \"[[Proud Mary]].\"<ref name=Y/> Before that, when Snow White first entered the theater from the rear, she seemed to surprise and even put-off the movie stars she was singing to, using a high-pitched imitation (bordering on parody) of the Disney cartoon. During the main number, before Rob Lowe's entrance, a crooning Merv Griffin introduced a procession of once famous Hollywood stars ranging from Alice Faye to Roy Rogers and Dale Evans to Vincent Price, which seemed more forced than natural as the elders were practically guided across the stage by male dancers (some dressed as chairs and tables). Also, there was no host that year. Instead, actors and actresses traded off, ranging from Tom Selleck (who opened) to Bob Hope and Lucille Ball (the latter died three weeks later). His no host theme was centered on \"compadres, costars, couples and companions,\" and his no host theme wouldn't be repeated until the Oscars of 2019.\n\nThe telecast also included a production number featuring what was introduced as \"The Stars of Tomorrow\" doing a number entitled \"I Wanna Be An Oscar Winner\" with all the participants being actors and actresses ranging from the age group of late teens to mid-20s (including Corey Feldman doing a Michael Jackson impression; Christian Slater sword fighting with Tyrone Power Jr.; Chad Lowe shouting \"I am a Thespian\"; Tracy Nelson ballet dancing; Patrick Dempsey tap dancing along the central set stairwell).<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uAQ9Taunh7w The Stars of Tomorrow: 1989 Oscars]</ref> Due largely to the show's opening number, and despite the shows stellar Nielson ratings, the show became a laughing-stock and went down in history as one of the worst moments in awards show and television history.  [[The Walt Disney Company]] sued for allegedly illegal use of Snow White's image.<ref>[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/looking-back-oscars-biggest-goof-21211 Looking back at Oscar's biggest goof|Hollywood Reporter]</ref> Meanwhile, Gregory Peck (a personal friend of Carr's) and a number of actors wrote and signed a letter of protest, demanding there never be a show like that again; Peck, in fact, threatened to return his past Oscar if it was ever repeated, which it wasn't. \n\nCarr's reputation in Hollywood never fully recovered from this setback, although his decision to change the award announcement from \"And the winner is...\" to \"And the Oscar goes to...\"<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PT7g5pWzOyw Why the 1989 Oscars Are the Worst Ever - Metaflix on YouTube]</ref> became the norm for awards shows in general, not just for the Oscars. Carr also first hired comedian [[Bruce Vilanch]] as head comedy writer of the show, a job Vilanch still held as of 2015 (Vilanch was redeemed the following year since his old friend Billy Crystal hosted for his first of many times: with Vilanch as his head writer).\n\n==Later work==\nThat same year Carr helmed the project ''Goya...A Life in Song'' with Freddie Gershon and CBS Records, a concept album and, later, an off-Broadway musical theater production written by [[Maury Yeston]] (''[[Nine (musical)|Nine]]'') and featuring [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]] as artist [[Francisco Goya]].  Still in development for a full Broadway production, the music has been recorded by Domingo with [[Dionne Warwick]] in English and [[Gloria Estefan]] in Spanish, and a version of the duet \"[[Till I Loved You (song)|Till I Loved You]]\" was a top 40 single for [[Barbra Streisand]] and [[Don Johnson]].\n\nCarr continued his work in theater, sponsoring the 1995 [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] productions of ''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (play)|Cyrano de Bergerac]]'' and ''[[Much Ado About Nothing]]'' at [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]]'s [[Kennedy Center]] and Broadway's [[Gershwin Theatre]]<ref>[https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1999-jun-30-mn-51594-story.html Allan Carr; Producer of 'Grease' and 'La Cage aux Folles' - Los Angeles Times]</ref>, earning 10 Tony nominations between them including one more for Carr.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/obituary-allan-carr-1105920.html Obituary: Allan Carr|The Independent]</ref>\nCarr had returned to [[Paramount Pictures]] to handle the re-release of ''[[Grease (film)|Grease]]'' in 1998, which included producing a [[VH1]] television special of the twentieth anniversary Hollywood \"premiere\" screening and party, and special edition re-releases of the video, DVD, and soundtrack album.\n\n==Production career==\nCarr was a film producer for numerous movies, including:\n*''[[The First Time (1969 film)|The First Time]]'' (1969)\n*''[[C.C. and Company]]'' (1970)\n*''[[Grease (film)|Grease]]'' (1978)\n*''[[Can't Stop the Music]]'' (1980)\n*''[[Grease 2]]'' (1982)\n*''[[Where the Boys Are '84]]'' (1984)\n*''[[Cloak & Dagger (1984 film)|Cloak & Dagger]]'' (1984)\n\n==Personal life and death==\nCarr died on June 29, 1999, in [[Beverly Hills, California]] from [[liver cancer]].<ref name=Y/> At the time of his death, he split his time between his homes in Beverly Hills and [[Palm Springs, California|Palm Springs]], and was working on bringing [[Ken Ludwig]]'s Tony-winning comedy ''[[Lend Me a Tenor]]'' to Australia and the UK, and was preparing a new Broadway show, ''The New Musical Adventures of Tom Sawyer''.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\nHis ashes were scattered at sea by Ann-Margret, Roger Smith and Martin Menard in front of his former Diamond Head estate on the island of Oahu, Hawaii.\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 2017 a documentary about Carr's life was released entitled ''[[The Fabulous Allan Carr]]''.  The director of ''The Fabulous Allan Carr'' [[Jeffrey Schwarz]] said, \"Although it was no secret that Allan Carr was gay, he never formally acknowledged it publicly. The word 'flamboyant' was used to describe him, a code word.\"<ref name=Y/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0139591}}\n* {{Find a Grave|23458|accessdate=September 14, 2010}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9mronRVvdmw The infamous 1989 opening of the Oscars on YouTube]\n* [https://vimeo.com/221448144 The same opening also on Vimeo]\n\n{{Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Screenplay 1980\u20132000}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carr, Allan}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[[Category:Film producers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Television producers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Jewish American screenwriters]]\n[[Category:LGBT Jews]]\n[[Category:Gay entertainers]]\n[[Category:LGBT businesspeople from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from California]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Illinois]]\n[[Category:American theatre managers and producers]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in California]]\n[[Category:Deaths from liver cancer]]\n[[Category:Lake Forest College alumni]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Writers from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Tony Award winners]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Television producers from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Illinois]]\n[[Category:LGBT producers]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGrease and Broadway success", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allan_Carr"}
{"title_page": "2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic by country and territory}}\n{{About|the status of the outbreak in different countries|information on how governments have been responding to the outbreak|National responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n[[File:COVID-19 Outbreak World Map per Capita.svg|thumb|Map of confirmed cases of COVID-19 per capita (as of {{today}}):\n{{legend|#900000|1,000+ confirmed cases per million}}\n{{legend|#c80200|500\u20131,000 confirmed cases per million}}\n{{legend|#ee7070|200\u2013500 confirmed cases per million}}\n{{legend|#ffC0C0|50\u2013200 confirmed cases per million}}\n{{legend|#ffdfe0|>0\u201350 confirmed cases per million}}\n{{legend|#eee|No confirmed cases or no data}}|455x455px|alt=]]\n[[File:COVID-19 Outbreak World Map.svg|thumb|Total confirmed cases of COVID-19 by country and territory (as of {{today}}):\n{{legend|#510000|100,000+ confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#900000|10,000\u201399,999 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#c80200|1,000\u20139,999 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ee7070|100\u2013999 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ffC0C0|10\u201399 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ffdfe0|1\u20139 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#eee|No confirmed cases or no data}}|455x455px|alt=]]\n[[File:COVID-19 Outbreak World Map Total Deaths per Capita.svg|thumb|Total confirmed deaths per capita of COVID-19 by country and territory (as of {{today}}):\n{{legend|#980043|100+ deaths per million}}\n{{legend|#dd1c77|10\u2013100 deaths per million}}\n{{legend|#df65b0|1\u201310 deaths per million}}\n{{legend|#c994c7|0.1\u20131 deaths per million}}\n{{legend|#d4b9da|0.01\u20130.1 deaths per million}}\n{{legend|#e0e0e0|No deaths or no data}}|455x455px|alt=]]\nThis article documents countries and territories affected by and their responses to the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|coronavirus]] responsible for the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ongoing 2019\u201320 pandemic]] first detected in [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]. It may not include all the most up-to-date major responses and measures.\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n{{clear|right}}\n{{clear|left}}\n\n== Pandemic by country and territory ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data}}\n=== Confirmed cases ===\n\nAs of {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|time|editlink=|ref=no}} on {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|date|editlink=|ref=no}}, a total of {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|confirmed|editlink=|ref=no}} cases are confirmed in more than 180 countries{{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|editlink=|ref=}} and 200 territories,<ref name=\"WOM\">{{cite web |url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries |title=Coronavirus Update (Live)\u2014Worldometer |website=www.worldometers.info |access-date=8 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129195657/https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries |archive-date=29 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> including 26 cruise ships.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mallapaty|first=Smriti|date=2020-03-26|title=What the cruise-ship outbreaks reveal about COVID-19|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-00885-w|journal=Nature|language=en|volume=580|issue=7801|pages=18|doi=10.1038/d41586-020-00885-w|pmid=32218546|quote=Since the Diamond Princess, at least 25 other cruise ships have confirmed COVID-19 cases.|via=|access-date=4 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401222028/https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-00885-w|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> There are {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|active|editlink=|ref=no}} active cases and {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|deaths|editlink=|ref=no}} deaths. The crude (preliminary) [[case fatality rate]] is {{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ratio|editlink=|ref=no}}.{{Cases in 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|editlink=|ref=}}\n\n=== Africa ===\n\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa}}\nCases have been confirmed in most African countries and territories. According to Michael Yao, WHO's head of emergency operations in Africa, early detection is vital because the continent's health systems \"are already overwhelmed by many ongoing disease outbreaks\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-51403865 |title=Coronavirus: Could African countries cope with an outbreak? |date=6 March 2020 |work=BBC News |access-date=9 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308100334/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-51403865 |archive-date=8 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Ahmed|first=Kaamil|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2020/mar/20/worlds-most-vulnerable-in-third-wave-for-covid-19-support-warn-experts|title=World's most vulnerable in 'third wave' for Covid-19 support, experts warn|date=2020-03-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-21|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321093509/https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2020/mar/20/worlds-most-vulnerable-in-third-wave-for-covid-19-support-warn-experts|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> As of 5{{nbsp}}April, cases have been confirmed in all African nations except for [[Comoros]] and [[Lesotho]], and the disputed state of the [[Sahrawi Arab Democratic Republic]]. There have been no reported cases in the territory of [[Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha]].\n\n=== Antarctica ===\n\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Antarctica}}\nAntarctica is the only continent not reached by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Taylor|first=Adam|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/03/24/one-continent-remains-untouched-by-coronavirus-antarctica/|title=One continent remains untouched by the coronavirus: Antarctica|date=March 24, 2020|work=The Washington Post|access-date=April 3, 2019|url-status=live|last2=Pitrelli|first2=Stefano|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401225655/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/03/24/one-continent-remains-untouched-by-coronavirus-antarctica/|archive-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Asia ===\n\n{{Main|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in Asia}}\nA cluster of mysterious [[pneumonia]] cases was detected in December 2019 in [[Wuhan]] and eventually spread to the rest of [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|China]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.cgtn.com/news/2019-12-31/Authorities-begin-testing-after-pneumonia-cases-in-central-China-MRPvtFbCve/index.html|title=27 cases of viral pneumonia reported in central China's Wuhan City|website=news.cgtn.com|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310153851/https://news.cgtn.com/news/2019-12-31/Authorities-begin-testing-after-pneumonia-cases-in-central-China-MRPvtFbCve/index.html|archive-date=10 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Afterwards, many other Asian countries started to confirm cases, with some of the most affected countries being [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|South Korea]], [[Malaysia]], and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|Iran]]. Sophisticated modelling of the outbreak suggests that while the number of cases in China would have been many times higher without interventions such as early detection and isolation of the infected, 66% fewer people would have been infected if China had implemented measures as little as a week earlier.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sample|first=Ian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/11/research-finds-huge-impact-of-interventions-on-spread-of-covid-19|title=Research finds huge impact of interventions on spread of Covid-19|date=2020-03-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-11|url-status=live|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320210318/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/11/research-finds-huge-impact-of-interventions-on-spread-of-covid-19|archive-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> As of 7 April, cases have been reported in all Asian countries except for [[Tajikistan]] and [[Turkmenistan]], while [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in North Korea|North Korea]] and [[Yemen]] have suspected cases. No cases have been reported in the disputed state of [[South Ossetia]].\n\n=== Europe ===\n\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe}}\nA small number of initial cases in Europe were reported [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France|in France]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Germany|Germany]] and other countries. On 21 February, a large outbreak was [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|reported in Italy]], mostly in the north near [[Milan]]. Cases grew rapidly as the outbreak spread across Europe. Cases have been reported in all European countries after [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Montenegro|Montenegro]] reported a case on 17 March, and in all European territories after the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Isle of Man|Isle of Man]] on 19 March, the disputed state of [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Transnistria|Transnistria]] on 21 March<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://a-tv.md/eng/index.php?newsid=78329 |title=AccentTv Another 14 cases of coronavirus have been confirmed in Moldova. Total number reached 80 |access-date=25 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403201635/http://a-tv.md/eng/index.php?newsid=78329 |archive-date=3 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the \u00c5land Islands|\u00c5land Islands]] on 22 March reported cases. No cases have been reported in [[Svalbard]], [[Alderney]], and [[Sark]]. The [[World Health Organization|WHO]] has declared [[Europe]] as the new centre of the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|virus]] after the situation improved in China.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51876784|title=Europe 'now epicentre of coronavirus pandemic'|date=2020-03-13|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-16|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316130008/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51876784|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== North America ===\n\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in North America}}\nThe first cases in North America were reported [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|in the United States]] in January 2020. Cases were reported in all North American countries after [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saint Kitts and Nevis|Saint Kitts and Nevis]] confirmed a case on 25 March, and in all North American territories except [[Bonaire]] and [[Saba]] (as of 5{{nbsp}}April).\n\n=== Oceania ===\n\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oceania}}\nCases have been confirmed in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Australia|Australia]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oceania#Easter Island|Easter Island]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Fiji|Fiji]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in French Polynesia|French Polynesia]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Guam|Guam]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Hawaii|Hawaii]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Caledonia|New Caledonia]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Zealand|New Zealand]], and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Papua New Guinea|Papua New Guinea]]. The first confirmed case was in Melbourne, Victoria on 25 January.<ref name=Case1>{{Cite web |url=https://www.health.gov.au/ministers/the-hon-greg-hunt-mp/media/first-confirmed-case-of-novel-coronavirus-in-australia|title=First confirmed case of novel coronavirus in Australia|date=25 January 2020|website=Australian Government Department of Health |access-date=3 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215171557/https://www.health.gov.au/ministers/the-hon-greg-hunt-mp/media/first-confirmed-case-of-novel-coronavirus-in-australia|archive-date=15 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Many small Pacific island nations have thus far avoided the outbreak by closing their borders. Cases have been reported in all Oceanian sovereign states except [[Kiribati]], [[Marshall Islands]], [[Federated States of Micronesia|Micronesia]], [[Nauru]], [[Palau]], [[Samoa]], [[Solomon Islands]], [[Tonga]], [[Tuvalu]], and [[Vanuatu]], and have not been reported in the associated states of [[Christmas Island]], [[Cocos (Keeling) Islands]], [[Cook Islands]], and [[Niue]]. Additionally, no cases have been reported in [[American Samoa]], [[Autonomous Region of Bougainville|the Autonomous Region of Bougainville]], [[Norfolk Island]], [[Pitcairn Islands]], [[Tokelau]], and [[Wallis and Futuna]].\n\n=== South America ===\n\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in South America}}\nAs of 19 March, cases have been confirmed in all South American countries: [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Argentina|Argentina]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Brazil|Brazil]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bolivia|Bolivia]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Chile|Chile]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Colombia|Colombia]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ecuador|Ecuador]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Guyana|Guyana]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Paraguay|Paraguay]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Peru|Peru]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Suriname|Suriname]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Uruguay|Uruguay]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Venezuela|Venezuela]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in French Guiana|the French overseas department of French Guiana]]. Cases were confirmed in all South American territories, as cases were confirmed in the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Falkland Islands|Falkland Islands]] on 3{{nbsp}}April.\n\nThe coronavirus was first reported in South America on 26 February when Brazil confirmed a case in S\u00e3o Paulo. Since then, governments across the region have taken an array of actions to protect their citizens and contain the spread of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.as-coa.org/articles/where-coronavirus-latin-america|title=Where Is the Coronavirus in Latin America?|first1=Luisa|last1=Horwitz|first2=Paola|last2=Nagovitch|first3=Holly K.|last3=Sonnel|first4=Carin|last4=Zissis|website=AS/COA|access-date=22 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322095058/https://www.as-coa.org/articles/where-coronavirus-latin-america|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== International conveyance ===\n\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships}}\nThe outbreak spread to several cruise ships including the [[Diamond Princess (ship)|''Diamond Princess'']], the ''[[Grand Princess]]'', the ''[[World Dream]]'', the [[MS Westerdam|MS ''Westerdam'']] and the [[MS Braemar|MS ''Braemar'']].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51433079 |title=Thousands on cruise free to go after virus tests |date=10 February 2020 |access-date=23 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222232522/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51433079 |archive-date=22 February 2020 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Marsh |first=Sarah |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/feb/23/coronavirus-outbreak-woman-tests-positive-after-disembarking-diamond-princess-live-news |title=Coronavirus outbreak: four cruise ship passengers test positive in UK\u2014live news |date=23 February 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=23 February 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223111701/https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/feb/23/coronavirus-outbreak-woman-tests-positive-after-disembarking-diamond-princess-live-news |archive-date=23 February 2020 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2020/02/22/coronavirus-cruise-ships-westerdam-passengers-lives-still-affected/4841819002/ |title=Coronavirus still wreaking havoc on lives of Westerdam passengers despite no cases on ship |last=Hines |first=Morgan |website=USA Today |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223002910/https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/cruises/2020/02/22/coronavirus-cruise-ships-westerdam-passengers-lives-still-affected/4841819002/ |archive-date=23 February 2020 |access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tribune242.com/news/2020/mar/12/breaking-five-bahamas-bound-cruise-ship-test-posit/|title=Cruise Ship Carrying Persons With Coronavirus 'Will Not Be Permitted To Dock'|date=13 March 2020|website=The Tribune|language=en|access-date=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327190153/http://www.tribune242.com/news/2020/mar/12/breaking-five-bahamas-bound-cruise-ship-test-posit/|archive-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCruise operators have started to either cancel or change their itineraries as countries across the world implement travel restrictions to curb the disease. Ports are refusing to accept cruise ships that have either been to Chinese ports or are carrying Chinese passengers.\n\nThe [[Cruise Lines International Association]] (CLIA), which represents 90% of cruise operators, announced the various precautionary measures being implemented by its members. All passengers who have traveled to or visited/transited through [[China]] (including [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macau]]) within 14 days before embarkation will be denied entry into cruise ships. Any persons in close contact with either suspected or diagnosed cases of coronavirus infection will also be denied entry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ship-technology.com/features/coronavirus-outbreak-2019-ncov-impact-cruise-operators-measures-tourism/|title=Coronavirus outbreak: How the 2019-nCoV is affecting the cruise industry|date=9 March 2020|website=Ship Technology|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304230047/https://www.ship-technology.com/features/coronavirus-outbreak-2019-ncov-impact-cruise-operators-measures-tourism/|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline of first confirmed cases by country or territory ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+First cases by country or territory\n|-\n! style=\"width:5em;\"  | Date\n! style=\"width:44em;\" | Country or territory\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2 January\n| {{flagdeco|CHN}} [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|China]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|13 January\n| {{flagdeco|THA}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Thailand|Thailand]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|16 January\n| {{flagdeco|JPN}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Japan|Japan]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|20 January\n| {{flagdeco|KOR}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|South Korea]] \u2022 {{flagdeco|USA}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|United States]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|21 January\n| ''{{flagdeco|TWN}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Taiwan|Taiwan]]{{efn-ua|name=fn1}}''\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|22 January\n| ''{{flagdeco|HKG}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Hong Kong|Hong Kong]]{{efn-ua|name=fn4}}'' \u2022 ''{{flagdeco|MAC}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Macau|Macau]]{{efn-ua|name=fn4}}''\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|23 January\n|  {{flagdeco|SGP}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Singapore|Singapore]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|24 January\n| {{flagdeco|FRA}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France|France]] \u2022 {{flagdeco|NPL}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nepal|Nepal]] \u2022 {{flagdeco|VNM}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Vietnam|Vietnam]]\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|25 January\n| {{flagdeco|AUS}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Australia|Australia]] \u2022 {{flagdeco|CAN}} [[2020 cor