lar Bishop of Sidon, [[Francesco Ravizza]].</ref>||20 December 1672||20 December 1672<ref>Almeida, p. 880.</ref>\n|-\n||61||[[Fernando IV Correia de Lacerda]]<ref>Correia was a doctor of Canon Law (Coimbra), and had been a Canon and Prebend of the Collegiate Church of Ourense. He was Inquisitor of Ebora and of Lisbon. Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 322 with note 4.</ref>||&nbsp;||17 July 1673<ref>Correia was named bishop of Porto by [[Peter II of Portugal|King Pedro II]] on 26 April 1673. Fl\u00f3rez, ''Espa\u00f1a Sagrada'' XXI, p. 226.</ref>||before 1 September 1683||1 September 1685\n|-\n||62||[[Jo\u00e3o de Sousa]]<ref>De Sousa was born in Lisbon in 1647; De Sousa's father was Majordomo of the Duke of Braganza, who became King [[John V of Portugal]]. His uncle was Archbishop of Evora. Fl\u00f3rez, ''Espa\u00f1a Sagrada'' XXI, pp. 227-229.</ref>||1647||6 December 1683<ref>Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 322, citing the ''Acta Consistoralia'' of [[Pope Innocent XI]].</ref>||24 September 1696<ref>De Sousa was appointed Archbishop of Braga: Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 126,  He was transferred to Lisbon on 1 October 1703: Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 397.</ref>||28 September 1710\n|}\n\n=== from 1700 to present ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!#!!Name!!Date of Birth!!Appointed!!Retired!!Date of Death\n|-\n||63||[[Jos\u00e9 Saldanha]], O.F.M.Disc.<ref>Saldanha's father Don Luis was the Majordomo of Queen Luisa. Fl\u00f3rez, ''Espa\u00f1a Sagrada XXI, pp. 229-230.</ref>||&nbsp;||17 December 1696<ref>Saldanha had previously been Bishop of Funchal (1690-1696). Ritzler-Sefrin, p. 322. Almeida, p. 882.</ref>||26 September 1708||26 September 1708<ref>Ritzler-Sefrin, p. 322, note 6.</ref>\n|-\n||64||'''[[Tom\u00e1s de Almeida]]'''<ref>Fl\u00f3rez, ''Espa\u00f1a Sagrada XXI, pp. 230-233.</ref>||5 October 1670||22 July 1709||7 December 1716<ref>Almeida was transferred to the diocese of Lisbon on 7 December 1716 by [[Pope Clement XI]]. He was named a Cardinal on 20 December 1737 by [[Pope Clement XII]], though he never came to Rome. He was sent his red biretta on 13 January 1738. On 22 June 1743 he was named Grand Inquisitor of Portugal. Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 8, no. 22; 397 with note 6.</ref>||22 February 1754\n|-\n|colspan=6 align=center bgcolor=#FFFFE0|''Vacant see (1716\u20131741)''\n|-\n||<center>X</center>||''Jo\u00e3o Maria''||bgcolor=#eee colspan=4 align=center|''Appointed in 1739 but not confirmed by Pope [[Clement XII]]''\n|-\n||65||[[Jos\u00e9 Maria da Evora]]<ref>He was born Jos\u00e9 da Fonseca. Jos\u00e9 Maria da Evora was his name as a Franciscan. He migrated to Rome in 1712. He had risen to be General of his Order, and, in the Roman Curia, was then named a member of the Consistorial Congregation, the Congregation for Indulgences, the Congregation of the Index, and the Holy Office of the Roman Inquisition. Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 346, note 2. Fl\u00f3rez, ''Espa\u00f1a Sagrada XXI, pp. 233-239.</ref>, [[O.F.M. Obs.]]||December 1690||2 January 1741<ref>Jos\u00e9 Maria da Evora was approved as Bishop of Porto by [[Pope Benedict XIV]] in the Consistory of 2 January 1741. Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 346. He was consecrated on 12 March 1741 by Cardinal Tom\u00e1s de Almeida, Patriarch of Lisbon.</ref>||16 June 1752||16 June 1752&nbsp;\n|-\n||66||[[Ant\u00f3nio de T\u00e1vora]], [[Order of Saint Augustine|O.E.S.A.]]<ref>Bishop Antonio de Souza de Tavora was the son of the second Marquez de Tavora, Antonio Luiz: {{cite book|author=Jos\u00e9 Augusto Ferreira|title=Memorias archeologico-historicas da cidade do Porto: fastos episcopaes e politicos; sec. VI-sec. XX|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9Q0rAQAAMAAJ|year=1924|publisher=Cruz|location=Braga|language=Portuguese|page=336}}</ref>||September 1690||28 March 1757<ref>Date of baptism: 21 September 1690. Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 346 with note 3.</ref>||1766||4 June 1766<ref>Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 346 with note 3.</ref>\n|-\n||67||[[Aleixo de Miranda Henriques]], O.P.||&nbsp;||1766<ref>Miranda served in Goa for six years, after which he was Qualificator of the Holy Inquisition in Lisbon. He was Bishop of Miranda from 1758 to 1770. He was transferred from the diocese of Miranda by [[Pope Clement XIV]] on 6 August 1770. He took possession of the diocese of Porto on 18 September 1770. Sainz de Barada, p. 111. Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 291 with note 4; p. 346 with note 4.</ref>||1771||&nbsp;\n|-\n||68||[[Jo\u00e3o Rafael de Mendon\u00e7a]]||24 April 1717||1771<ref>Mendon\u00e7a was the son of the conde de Val de dos Res, and brother of the Patriarch of Lisbon. He was a [[Hieronymites|Hieronymite]], and held a doctorate in theology from Coimbra. He was elected to the diocese of Pinhel, but was transferred to Porto before his consecration. He was consecrated by his brother in Lisbon on 10 November 1771. Sainz de Barada, p. 111. Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 346 with note 5.</ref>||1773||1773\n|-\n||69||[[Louren\u00e7o Correia de S\u00e1 Benevides]]||25 March 1741<ref>Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 324 note 6, state that the date of birth was 5 March, not 25 March. De S\u00e1 was born at Guimar\u00e3es (diocese of Braga). He held the Licenciate in Canon Law (Coimbra).</ref>||18 December 1795||1798||6 June 1798\n|-\n||70||[[Ant\u00f3nio de S\u00e3o Jos\u00e9]], O.Cart.||April 1745<ref>Fr. Antonio de S. Joseph was baptised as Ant\u00f3nio de Castro on 30 April 1745. Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 354, with note 7.</ref>||13 November 1798<ref>Fr. Antonio was presented by the Queen on 11 August 1798, and approved by [[Pope Pius VI]] on 13 November.</ref>||12 April 1814<ref>In 1808 he organized the anti-French Junta in Porto. He was nominated to the See of Lisbon by the Regent in 1809, but was not confirmed by [[Pope Pius VII]]. Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 354, note 7.</ref>||12 April 1814\n|-\n||71||[[Jo\u00e3o Magalh\u00e3es de Avelar]]||22 December 1754||29 April 1816<ref>He was nominated on 17 December 1814, but his confirmation by Pope Pius VII was delayed until the Pope was released from imprisonment at Fontainebleau and repatriated to Rome. Ritzler-Sefrin, VII, p. 313.</ref>||16 May 1833||16 May 1833\n|-\n||72||[[Manuel de Santa In\u00eas]]||bgcolor=#eee colspan=4 align=center|''Elected in 1833 but unconfirmed by [[Gregory XVI]]''\n|-\n||73||[[Jer\u00f3nimo da Costa Rebelo]]||&nbsp;||1843||1854||1854\n|-\n||74||[[Ant\u00f3nio Fonseca Moniz]]||&nbsp;||1854||1859||1859\n|-\n|colspan=6 align=center bgcolor=#FFFFE0|''Vacant see (1859\u20131862)''\n|-\n||75||[[Jo\u00e3o de Fran\u00e7a Castro e Moura]]||&nbsp;||1862||16 October 1868<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecclesia.pt/porto/destaque/cardeal_americo.htm |title=Am\u00e9rico Ferreira dos Santos Silva (1830-1899) |accessdate=2006-12-12 |last=Azevedo |first=Carlos A. Moreira |date=1999-01-27 |work=Ecclesia.pt |language=Portuguese |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061012010955/http://www.ecclesia.pt/porto/destaque/cardeal_americo.htm |archivedate=2006-10-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref>||16 October 1868\n|-\n|colspan=6 align=center bgcolor=#FFFFE0|''Vacant see (1868\u20131871)''\n|-\n||76||'''[[Am\u00e9rico Ferreira dos Santos Silva]]'''||16 January 1829||26 June 1871||21 January 1899||21 January 1899\n|-\n||77||[[Ant\u00f3nio Jos\u00e9 de Sousa Barroso]]<ref>Diocese do Porto, [http://www.diocese-porto.pt/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=702:d-antonio-jose-de-sousa-barroso-&catid=73:bispos-porto&Itemid=111 ''D. Ant\u00f3nio Jos\u00e9 de Sousa Barroso (1899\u20131918)'']; retrieved: 2017-09-29. (in Portuguese)</ref>||4 November 1854||20 May 1899||31 August 1918||31 August 1918\n|-\n||78||[[Ant\u00f3nio Barbosa Le\u00e3o]]<ref>Diocese do Porto, [http://www.diocese-porto.pt/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=699:d-antonio-barbosa-leao&catid=73:bispos-porto&Itemid=111 ''D. Ant\u00f3nio Barbosa Le\u00e3o (1919\u20131929)'']; retrieved: 2017-09-29. (in Portuguese)</ref>||17 October 1860||16 July 1919||21 June 1929||21 June 1919\n|-\n||79||[[Ant\u00f3nio Augusto de Castro Meireles]]<ref>Diocese do Porto, [http://www.diocese-porto.pt/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=695:d-antonio-augusto-de-castro-meireles&catid=73:bispos-porto&Itemid=111 ''D. Ant\u00f3nio Augusto de Castro Meireles (1929\u20131942)'']; retrieved: 2017-09-29. (in Portuguese)</ref>||13 August 1885||21 June 1929<ref name=\"suc\">Meireles was appointed Coadjutor bishop (i.e. appointed as successor of the preceding bishop before the latter's retirement or death) on 20 June 1928.</ref>||29 March 1942<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.agencia.ecclesia.pt/diocese/pub/11/noticia.asp?jornalid=11&noticiaid=22076 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927204642/http://www.agencia.ecclesia.pt/diocese/pub/11/noticia.asp?jornalid=11&noticiaid=22076 | url-status=dead | archive-date=2007-09-27 | title=D. Ant\u00f3nio Augusto de Castro Meireles | accessdate=2006-12-12 | author=Diocese of Angra | date=2005-08-09 | work=Ag\u00eancia Ecclesia - Ag\u00eancia de Not\u00edcias da Igreja Cat\u00f3lica Portuguesa | language=Portuguese}} </ref>||29 March 1942\n|-\n||80||[[Agostinho de Jesus e Sousa]]<ref>Diocese do Porto, [http://www.diocese-porto.pt/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=691:d-agostinho-de-jesus-de-sousa&catid=73:bispos-porto&Itemid=111 ''D. Agostinho de Jesus e Sousa (1942\u20131952)'']; retrieved: 2017-09-29. (in Portuguese)</ref>||7 March 1877||16 May 1942<ref>Agostinho de Jesus e Sousa had previously been Coadjutor bishop of Lamego (1921\u20131935), then Bishop of Lamego (1935\u20131942).</ref>||21 February 1952||21 February 1952\n|-\n||81||[[Ant\u00f3nio Ferreira Gomes]]<ref>Diocese do Porto, [http://www.diocese-porto.pt/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=689:d-antonio-ferreira-gomes&catid=73:bispos-porto&Itemid=111 ''D. Ant\u00f3nio Ferreira Gomes (1952\u20131982)'']; retrieved: 2017-09-29. (in Portuguese)</ref>||10 May 1906||13 July 1952||2 May 1982||13 April 1989\n|-\n||82||[[J\u00falio Tavares Rebimbas]]||21 January 1922||12 February 1982||13 June 1997||6 December 2010\n|-\n||83